<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / Yeltsin signs decree on free sale of land
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LEYLA BOULTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT Boris Yeltsin yesterday signed an historic decree allowing the
free sale of land, in a move crucial to the reform of Russian agriculture,
writes Leyla Boulton from Moscow.
The decree follows two years of wrangling, during which the now-dissolved
Russian parliament had accepted private ownership of land but set a 10-year
moratorium on its sale by private citizens. Yesterday's decree lays the
foundations for a mortgage system, enabling banks to lend money to farmers
using land as collateral, and sets out reforms to the state and collective
farms which still dominate Russia's ailing agricultural sector.
However, Mr Victor Khlystun, the agriculture minister, said the decree -
which has yet to be published in its final version - does not allow
foreigners to buy land. They would be allowed to lease it 'under certain
conditions', which he did not spell out.
</TEXT>
