<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / Domestic site likely for Mercedes plant
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE, Motor Industry Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GERMANY is emerging ahead of Britain, France and the Czech Republic as the
most likely location for a new plant to assemble Mercedes-Benz' planned
small car.
The decision hinges on negotiations with unions on labour changes to reduce
costs at the plant.
Mr Dieter Zetsche, product development director of Mercedes-Benz car
division, said a decision would be made before the end of the year. The
favourite site is at Rastatt in south-west Germany, where the company
already carries out some final assembly of its E-Class executive and luxury
cars.
However, other sites in Germany and elsewhere in Europe are being
investigated through the London office of management consultants Arthur D
Little.
Mr Zetsche said building the plant at an existing site was the favoured
option as this would be cheaper, although the unions would have to agree to
meet the necessary cost targets.
'If we were to locate it in Germany, it would most probably be in Rastatt,
where we have a huge site.'
A decision to go ahead with the car, which would be smaller than a
Volkswagen Golf or a Ford Escort, is expected in the next two months. The
plant would have a capacity for 200,000 cars a year.
German unions are anxious to keep the small car plant in the country to help
offset the loss of 37,400 jobs in Germany that Mercedes is eliminating the
three years from 1992 to 1994.
The company has recently announced that it is to build a Dollars 300m
assembly plant in Alabama in the US to produce up to 60,000 four-wheel drive
leisure utility vehicles a year from 1997. It will also start production
late next year of a multi-purpose vehicle in Spain.
