<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / Allianz calls for steps to reduce insurance losses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ALLIANZ, Europe's largest insurance company, has called on its corporate
clients to co-operate in implementing a package of radical measures designed
to reduce huge losses in the German industrial insurance sector
Mr Manfred Illner, a director of Allianz's main domestic insurance
subsidiary, outlined six steps which the group wants to implement in order
to cut losses in this sector.
Simply raising premiums to the level where the business was again profitable
was not acceptable, Mr Illner said on Tuesday night, nor was withdrawing
from this area of the insurance market as has happened in other countries.
He urged Allianz's corporate clients to co-operate in measures which range
from setting premiums which are more appropriate to the scale of the risk,
to introducing better risk-management procedures in companies and agreeing
limits to maximum coverage levels.
This, Mr Illner warned, was the only way of keeping Germany insurable, 'and
German industry must remain insurable so that it, and Germany as a location
for industry, can maintain their position.'
Last year, Allianz, the market leader in the German insurance industry, lost
DM100m (Pounds 40.6m) in the industrial risks sector, and the German
market's 10 biggest losses in the engineering sector alone amounted to
DM125m. One hail storm in May this year caused a pay-out of DM28m to just
one client, Munich airport.
Over the past five years the German insurance market has lost DM2.6bn in
industrial fire insurance alone, but there has also been a significant
increase in the number and size of claims in other sectors. The German
insurance market is the biggest in Europe.
These sharply increased losses reflect a number of factors, including the
cost and sophistication of the technology which is covered by insurance, an
increase in crimes such as arson, and poor weather conditions.
