<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / Labour fires broadside at Spanish reforms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TOM BURNS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MADRID
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
X:IMPORTANT talks on wage restraint and labour market reforms in Spain
opened under a pall yesterday as unions announced nation-wide demonstrations
on November 25 in protest at the government's economic policy.
Union leaders, who are meeting government ministers and representatives of
the employers' confederation, agreed to continue negotiating the so-called
social pact next week but held out little hope of any agreement after the
first round of talks.
The call for demonstrations underlined the grave task facing the government
as it seeks to persuade the unions to accept an incomes policy pegging wages
to below the inflation rate over the next three years, and an overhaul of
labour regulations to lower the cost of dismissals.
Officials and employers fear that Spanish union militancy is being fuelled
by events in France. 'The climbdown over Air France is the worst possible
news for us because we have to do everything the French government should be
doing and more,' said a leading Barcelona industrialist.
Union leaders at the social pact talks were in part responding to what they
see as government intransigence over the negotiations and in part to the
groundswell of rank-and-file unrest.
'The government is wrecking the talks, not us,' said Mr Antonio Gutierrez,
leader of Comisiones Obreras, the Communist party-led union. The government
has insisted that it will impose wage restraint and labour market reforms
before the end of the year if there is no agreement with the unions.
Unrest is running high among Spain's 70,000 public sector steelworkers
following a decision by INI, the state-holding company, to defer until the
outcome of the social pact talks a wage and productivity package agreed in
June. INI's agreement with its unions was marginally more generous than the
incomes policy the government is currently backing.
Union leaders at companies such as CSI, the state's integrated steel
concern, and CASA, the aerospace manufacturer, said they would prepare
strike action following a meeting with the INI management yesterday.
Meanwhile, the first of several planned industrial stoppages took place
yesterday at the three plants run by SEAT, troubled subsidiary of
Volkswagen. The four-hour strike went ahead despite a promise by Mr Jose
Ignacio Lopez Arriortua, the Spanish-born VW board member, that job losses
would be minimal because workers would be re-hired under a scheme to
increase the proportion of SEAT compoments manufactured in Spain.
In Spain's biggest labour shakeout to date, VW announced last week it was
closing SEAT's Zona Franca plant in Barcelona and shed 9,000 jobs, 3,000 of
them through voluntary retirement. The Barcelona-based regional government
of Catalonia has since said it will provide credit lines for component
manufacturers setting up in the Zona Franca plant to supply SEAT.
</TEXT>
