<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / Tietmeyer rejects calls for interest rate cuts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Bundesbank president, Mr Hans Tietmeyer, yesterday rejected calls from
Germany's independent research institutes to accelerate the pace of cuts in
short-term interest rates .
Mr Tietmeyer said that for the time being there was no scope for another cut
in rates, rebutting the institutes' argument - contained in their autumn
report published early this week - that further reductions would help the
country emerge from recession.
'The Bundesbank rejects all calls to stimulate the economy with forced
interest cuts,' Mr Tietmeyer said at a conference in Frankfurt.
'Unlike the institutes, we see no narrow link between short-term interest
rate cuts and growth and employment.'
He said the rate cuts last week were justified by the more moderate
development of money supply growth and inflation in recent months.
Last Thursday the central bank reduced both the Lombard and the discount
rate by half a percentage point, to 6.25 and 5.75 per cent respectively.
The repo rate, which provides liquidity to the banking system, was cut more
modestly, from 6.67 to 6.4 per cent.
Voicing the Bundesbank's conviction that long-term rates are more important
for German industry than short-term ones, he argued that the institutes had
underestimated the risks of a rise in long-term rates if the Bundesbank
delivered further, substantial cuts in the discount and Lombard rates.
He said that neither the absolute level of current interest rates, nor the
'inverted' structure of the interest rate curve (whereby short-term rates
are higher than long-term ones) acted as a brake on investment in German
industry. On the contrary, those who wanted to invest could borrow money at
long-term interest rates which were almost 'incomparably favourable' in
international terms.
Mr Tietmeyer said there was no doubt that the central bank would hold to its
course of gradual rate reductions, but not at the price of creating new
uncertainties for the financial markets as regards German monetary policy.
Later in his speech Mr Tietmeyer repeated a statement he has made several
times since he succeeded Mr Helmut Schlesinger as Bundesbank president at
the beginning of October: that the Bundesbank would not act as 'the central
bank for Europe' in the run-up to European monetary union. Its paramount
objective will remain domestic: to squeeze inflation out of Germany and
thereby preserve the value of the D-Mark.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>DEZ  Germany, EC.
</CN>
