<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / Top Conservatives question future of unified Budget
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHITEHALL officials and senior Conservatives have put a serious question
mark over the long-term future of the Treasury's new 'unified' Budget.
A month before Mr Kenneth Clarke unveils the first joint tax and spending
package on November 30, some ministers believe the new system - combining
the old spring Budget and autumn public spending statement - cannot last.
The change is being condemned in Whitehall as a clever administrative reform
which risks going horribly wrong. It is viewed within Conservative Central
Office as a grievous political error.
One senior Conservative commented bluntly: 'The change could cost us the
next general election.' The party had won the last three elections by going
to the country within weeks of announcing income tax cuts in March. No one
had considered that it would make no sense to call an election in January.
The initial enthusiasm of some in the cabinet for the move has been damped
down by the Treasury's refusal to discuss tax changes during the current
spending negotiations. Ministers are now describing the phrase 'unified
Budget' as a misnomer.
Party managers have also realised that switching the Budget to November may
make it more difficult to manage the government's small and fractious
majority at Westminster.
In the past, the finance bill has been debated after the start of the
financial year in April. The fact that Budget tax changes were already in
place discouraged backbench rebellions.
But now a five-month gap between announcements in November and
implementation the following April will give potential Conservative rebels
ample time to marshall their forces, particularly if the outlook for the
economy changes during that period.
Mr Clarke might partially circumvent the threat by giving immediate effect
on November 30 to any increases in excise duties and value added tax. But he
cannot bring forward changes in corporation and income tax.
In Whitehall the new system is being attacked on both economic and political
grounds. Officials fear that the requirement to take critical decisions
nearly six months before the start of the financial year could lead to fatal
misjudgments over taxation and borrowing.
That problem is particularly acute this year because of the uncertainty over
the pace of economic recovery and the size of the borrowing requirement. The
chancellor will be basing his decisions on a forecast of public borrowing
for next year which contains a huge margin of error.
The consensus among Whitehall's mandarins is that Mr Clarke should announce
a significant increase in taxes because the economic recovery is well
founded and public borrowing remains much too high. But they acknowledge
that since the evidence of recovery will remain patchy until next year the
political pressures are in the opposite direction.
</TEXT>
