<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / A city on edge as killings dull hopes for an end to
violence: The mood in Belfast after the latest deaths
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM COONE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BELFAST this week is living on its nerves, its population once again peering
into the abyss.
Since last Saturday, 14 people have been killed and more than 60 injured in
an upsurge of political violence. An IRA bomb on the Shankill Road - killing
10 and wounding over 50, most of them shoppers  - has been followed by an
intensified campaign by Loyalist paramilitaries to gun down Catholics
indiscriminately.
'We just don't know where or who is going to get hit next. We are back where
we were 20 years ago. I just feel like shutting up shop and leaving,' said a
frightened woman owner of a newsagents on the Crumlin Road in west Belfast.
Many shops in Catholic and Protestant neighbourhoods were shut yesterday,
either out of respect for the funerals of six of the latest victims, out of
fear of further trouble, or simply because their owners can no longer make
ends meet.
In some streets in the Protestant Shankill, and the Catholic Falls and
Ardoyne areas of west Belfast, unemployment is higher than 50 per cent.
Hard-faced young men hang around on street corners and watch armoured cars
cruise past on patrol, while two army helicopters and an aircraft circling
constantly overhead add to the sense of foreboding.
A man on the Shankill Road watching the crowd gathering for the funeral
service of five of Saturday's bomb victims said: 'We Protestants feel
abandoned by the government. As long as the IRA can get away with atrocities
like this there are going to be more and more killings by the Loyalists.'
Hundreds of wreaths had been placed on the pavement outside the fishmonger's
shop on the Shankill Road where the bomb exploded. Among messages of
sympathy from friends and families, one had a more chilling message: 'With
deepest sympathy from the officers and members of the Red Hand Commando,'
the loyalist paramilitary group.
A bulldozer was yesterday clearing the gap in the terrace where the shop had
stood. On the side wall, a paramilitary plaque still hung in full view. It
said: 'West Belfast Brigade Headquarters. Ulster Defence Association.'
Less than half a mile away, over 1,000 people attended the funeral of Thomas
Begley, the IRA man who planted the bomb and killed himself in the process.
At one point, Mr Gerry Adams, leader of Sinn Fein, the political wing of the
IRA, shouldered the coffin. Earlier this week, Mr Adams had said that he
wanted the IRA to go into retirement.
As one observer remarked, Mr Adams' action was as if to say that the peace
initiative launched with Mr John Hume, the leader of the SDLP, just a month
ago had also been pronounced dead.
Northern Ireland Secretary Sir Patrick Mayhew said newspaper photographs had
shown 'people in abject misery as a result of what happened in the Shankill
Road, and today we see Mr Adams carrying the coffin, supporting one of those
who did it'.
Tomorrow, Mr John Major, the prime minister and Mr Albert Reynolds, his
Irish counterpart, will meet in Brussels to discuss the Hume-Adams
initiative.
Yesterday the mood in the working-class housing estates of west Belfast was
not one of hopeful anticipation for what may be discussed in Brussels. Hopes
here are simpler and narrower - that friends, family and oneself will not be
the next victims.
Adams condemned for carrying bomber's coffin, Page 8
</TEXT>
