<HEADLINE>
FT  27 OCT 93 / Survey of French Finance and Investment (10): Risky business
 -Profile: Credit Lyonnais
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
OF ALL the financial companies primed for privatisation by the Balladur
government, Credit Lyonnais is by far the most risky - and the most
exciting.
Credit Lyonnais is now counting the cost of five years of aggressive
expansion under its chairman, Jean-Yves Haberer.
It has been left with an impressive European retail banking network and a
bulging junk bond portfolio, but with a large number of bad loans on its
books and a trail of losses that added up to FFr1.8bn in 1992 and to FFr1bn
in the first half of this year.
Mr Haberer recently confirmed that he was considering a post at another
company.
The hot tip to replace him is Jean Peyrelevade, the highly-respected head of
the UAP insurance group, who is one of the few figures in French finance
deemed capable of taking on Credit Lyonnais.
Nevertheless the Credit Lyonnais scenario is not entirely grim. Its big
corporate catastrophes are now over. As the economy recovers it should start
reaping the benefits of its impressive domestic network and of Mr Haberer's
best legacy, its brand new European network.
