<HEADLINE>
FT  27 OCT 93 / Survey of French Finance and Investment (8): A prudent
approach - Profile: AGF
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
SO far Assurances Generales de France (AGF), the third largest insurer in
France after UAP and Axa, has been relatively resilient in spite of the
pressures on the French insurance industry. It saw net profits fall to
FFr1.5bn in 1992 from FFr2.7bn in 1991, but recently reported that profits
had stabilised at FFr1.4bn in the first half of 1993.
AGF has not been unaffected by the recession. Banque du Phenix, one of its
banking subsidiaries, last year was hit by the property squeeze and this
year it has borne heavy losses on its stake in Comptoir des Entrepreneurs.
However AGF, under the chairmanship of Michel Albert, has been less exposed
to the more volatile areas of the economy than UAP and GAN, its fellow
state-controlled insurers, and has benefited from his long-term strategy of
protecting profitability rather than chasing market share. Mr Albert has
already said that he expects the second half of 1993 to show an improvement
over the first.
AGF has adopted the same prudent approach to international expansion as to
the management of its domestic business. Yet it scored a coup last year by
taking a stake in AMB, the German insurer, beating UAP in the race to become
the first big French insurer with a sizeable presence in Germany.
