<PROFILE>_AN-DJ0CNAGVFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>931027
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  27 OCT 93 / Survey of French Finance and Investment (7): A watershed for
finance - Privatisation will bring with it big changes for banks and
insurers
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
WHEN Edmond Alphandery, the French economy minister, this summer announced
the names of the 21 companies scheduled for privatisation by his government,
some of France's most powerful financial groups appeared high on his list.
The Balladur privatisation drive has important implications for the French
financial sector. Banque Nationale de Paris (BNP), the first of the
government's share sales, has already been sold as eventually will Credit
Lyonnais. The sales of Union des Assurances de Paris (UAP) and Assurances
Generales de France (AGF), the powerful insurers, are expected next year
followed by the GAN Group.
These share sales will mark a watershed in the development of the French
financial system by heralding significant changes in its traditionally close
relationship with the state and by forcing the old state-controlled banks
and insurers to carve out new roles as private sector companies.
The precise nature of the state's relationship with these groups is shrouded
in secrecy. In theory the government has no direct influence over the public
sector banks and insurers in terms of their day-to-day management and
strategy. But in practice it has exerted significant influence over both
areas - directly and indirectly.
The source of the government's direct influence is its power to hire and
fire the chairmen of the companies it controls. A change of government
usually triggers an elaborate game of musical chairs as the new
administration replaces the old appointees with its own candidates.
It is scarcely a coincidence that the chairman of almost all France's big
banks and insurers started their careers as political advisers to prominent
politicians or as civil servants in important ministries. Once in their new
posts they can reshuffle the senior management of their companies, often by
bringing in people from their old ministries.
Some observers suspect that the presence of so many fonctionnaires, or civil
servants, has instilled a bureaucratic culture in France's large financial
groups. They claim banks and insurers have been left with top-heavy
management structures, a reluctance to shed staff and a cautious approach to
international expansion.
Privatisation should bring the fonctionnaire era to an end. The chairmen
will then be appointed, as with any other private sector company, by the
shareholders, making future appointees more likely to be professional
financiers than well-connected bureaucrats.
Similarly privatisation should make the banks and insurers less vulnerable
to indirect pressure from the state in areas such as interest rate policy
and investment strategy.
Anglo-Saxon sceptics tend to assume that the French government simply
dictates interest rate policy to the state banks, BNP and Credit Lyonnais,
by telling them whether and when they can change base rates. In practice the
system is more subtle in that the political appointees at the top of the big
banks are not only virtually guaranteed to be sympathetic to the
government's aims, but know instinctively what it expects them to do.
Conspiracy theorists cite as evidence of the state's influence events of
earlier this year when the French banks incurred heavy losses by holding
base rates at a time when the Bank of France raised its short term lending
rates as part of the government's battle to defend the franc. They also
claim it is instructive that BNP and Credit Lyonnais are usually the first
to cut base rates, while any increases tend to be led by the privatised
banks, Societe Generale or Credit du Nord (part of Paribas).
The banks claim publicly that the government has no control, either direct
or indirect, over base rates. Privately they admit that, since the
privatisation of Societe Generale in the late 1980s, the system has been
more flexible in that at least one of the Big Three retail banks is
genuinely independent of the state. The sale of BNP and Credit Lyonnais,
should erode the government's influence even further.
Similarly the government should find it much more difficult to use the state
banks and insurers as tools in its industrial policy by 'suggesting' that
they take strategic stakes in other public sector companies. The government
claims that such investment decisions are taken voluntarily. But the row a
few years ago when BNP tried to avoid taking a stake in Air France suggests
otherwise.
However this ritual may well survive privatisation. The entire French
corporate sector is riddled with cross-shareholdings and 'sweetheart' deals.
Moreover the government has been at pains to ensure that it has some
residual influence over the privatisation candidates by appointing its own
candidates to lead them into the private sector. Rene Thomas, veteran
chairman of BNP, has already been replaced by Michel Pebereau, who was
involved with the privatisation of Credit Commercial de France (CCF).
Jean-Yves Haberer, chairman of Credit Lyonnais, is mooted as the next
target. He is expected to move to the chairman's seat at Credit Nationale,
paving the way for Jean Peyrelevade, chairman of UAP, to take over at Credit
Lyonnais.
But old habits die hard. A few years ago Marc Vienot, chairman of the
thoroughly privatised Societe Generale, was searching for an heir apparent.
His choice was not, as one might expect, an experienced banker from Societe
Generale itself or one of its competitors, but Daniel Bouton, a career civil
servant.
</TEXT>
<XX>
