<HEADLINE>
FT  27 OCT 93 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow shows resilience to poor
consumer data
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
AFTER profit-taking and news of weakening consumer confidence had depressed
US stocks in early trading, share prices recovered their losses to end the
day mostly flat, writes Patrick Harverson in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average closed just 1.12 down at 3,672.49, well off
its low for the day of 3,654.05. The Standard &amp; Poor's 500 ended 0.10 up at
464.30, while the American SE composite was 1.94 off at 473.64 and the
Nasdaq composite lost 4.29 at 765.46. NYSE volume was 285m shares.
Although prices firmed at the opening, it was clear that market participants
were ready to take some quick profits after Monday's gains when the Dow rose
to an all-time high. Consequently an early 10-point climb for the Dow turned
into a 10-point loss within the first hour of trading.
Profit-taking was not confined to the big blue chip industrial and cyclical
shares which lifted the Dow into record territory on Monday; secondary
stocks posted their second straight day of declines.
Concern about the economy deepened yesterday after the Conference Board
announced that its index of consumer confidence had dropped in October to
59.4, down from a revised 63.8 for the previous month.
The news lifted bond prices for the first time in three days, but initially
depressed equity market sentiment, until a round of buying mid-afternoon
helped most stocks recover their early losses. Only secondary issues traded
on the Nasdaq market remained firmly rooted in negative territory.
IBM rose Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 46 1/8 after the troubled computer giant
unveiled a third-quarter loss of 12 cents a share, smaller than analysts had
expected. Investors were not sure what to make of the data, with the stock
rising initially, then falling, only to recover strongly in late trading.
Leading Dow stocks which were in good form on Monday wilted on
profit-taking. Eastman Kodak receded Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars 57 7/8 and
Aluminum Co of America Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars 69 5/8 .
RJR Nabisco lost Dollars  1/8 to Dollars 5 1/4 but rallied to end unchanged
at Dollars 5 3/8 , after the tobacco and foods company unveiled
third-quarter net income sharply lower than a year ago because of the
cigarette price war.
Pharma Resources rose Dollars 3 to Dollars 16 7/8 in heavy trade after the
US Food and Drug Administration said it would review the company's
applications for generic drugs, a decision that opens the way for the
company to seek new product approvals.
National Health Laboratories dropped Dollars 2 1/4 to Dollars 13 1/4 in
volume of 3.2m shares after the company issued a warning about lower
third-quarter revenues.
Canada
TORONTO rebounded from earlier sluggishness to close well ahead as the
market shed some of its post-election nervousness.
Traders said they expect the TSE 300 index, which gained 31.9 at 4,187.1
yesterday, to continue improving on the back of the strength of US shares in
recent days. An analyst commented that the gain 'reflected additional
confidence in the economy and a move to catch up with Dow Jones'.
Advances led declines by 366 to 327 after volume of 51.4m shares valued at
CDollars 625.9m.
</TEXT>
