<HEADLINE>
FT  27 OCT 93 / International Company News: Carter Holt in Chile move
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By AP-DJ
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WELLINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
NEW ZEALAND-based forestry concern Carter Holt Harvey is seeking to convert
its 30.5 per cent indirect ownership in Copec, its Chilean forestry and
fishing associate, into a direct ownership structure, AP-DJ reports from
Wellington.
Carter Holt, which is controlled by a joint venture between US-based
International Paper and New Zealand-based Brierley Investments, said it had
initiated the preliminary legal steps necessary for such a move.
The New Zealand company currently holds its Copec stake through a joint
venture with Angellini Group of Chile.
Copec, formally known as Compania de Petroleos de Chile, is one of Chile's
largest industrial companies, with operations in forestry, fishing, energy
and retailing.
Carter Holt said the current ownership structure for its holding in Copec
limits its involvement with the company.
The New Zealand company sees various opportunities to add value to Copec,
and having a direct stake in the company would allow some of these
opportunities to be realised.
Carter Holt's stake in Copec is worth around NZDollars 1bn (USDollars 555m)
and it wants to manage this investment actively. The group has in the past
talked of selling its Chilean investments, but said this is not now being
considered.
The company declined to say whether it planned to increase its stake in
Copec.
Copec is 61 per cent-owned by Inversiones y Desarrollo Los Andes, which is
in turn 50 per cent owned by Carter Holt and 50 per cent by Angellini, a
family-owned Chilean concern.
</TEXT>
