<DATE>931027
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  27 OCT 93 / International Company News: Swedish opposition to
Volvo-Renault merger mounts
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Opposition mounted in Sweden yesterday to Volvo's planned merger of its
vehicle manufacturing with Renault of France in spite of a detailed defence
of its plans published by the company.
For the first time, united trade union support for the deal cracked as 900
civil engineers within Volvo called for the merger to be postponed until
Renault is privatised and a committee representing more than 5,000 white
collar workers decided to use their small shareholding to vote against the
accord at the November 9 extraordinary general meeting on the issue.
At the same time, two influential newspapers voiced their opposition. Mr
Mats Svegfors, editor of Svenska Dagbladet, the respected conservative
daily, wrote that if necessary the government should step in to prevent
Volvo, the country's leading manufacturing group, falling under French
control.
Dagens Industri, Sweden's financial daily, said the merger should be delayed
until 1996, after Renault had been freed from state control. Volvo said
momentum was building up against the merger, but said it was not clear Volvo
shareholders shared this view.
The company circulated a 66-page document to shareholders saying the merger
was a 'logical and necessary extension' of a three-year old alliance between
Volvo and Renault.
It said Volvo's 35 per cent share in the merged company would be 'an
important cornerstone' in a radically restructured Volvo which would broaden
its interests to include a 100 per cent share in the cash-rich Branded
Consumer Products, part of Procordia, a food and pharmaceutical group
jointly controlled by Volvo and the Swedish state.
Mr Pehr Gyllenhammar, Volvo's chairman, insisted Volvo would retain a large
influence in the merged Renault-Volvo company in spite of the 65 per cent
weighting in favour of French interests. He said Mr Lennart Jeansson, head
of Volvo cars, and Mr Karl-Erling Trogen, head of Volvo Heavy Trucks, would
respectively become chief financial officer and head of trucks and buses in
Renault-Volvo on a five-man management board headed by Mr Louis Schweitzer,
the Renault chief executive. Mr Gyllenhammar said Renault was making the
biggest foreign investment in Sweden, and was hardly likely to damage this
by running down Volvo's Swedish base.
In a typically stirring evocation, he said Volvo would be contributing to
the process of building Europe. 'We have to realise that such work requires
both giving and taking,' he said.
Aktiespararna, the Swedish small shareholders association, which has led
opposition to the merger, dismissed the Volvo leaflet, saying it gave no
clearer picture of the valuation of Volvo's assets in the merger. It
repeated its view that Volvo had no guarantees that Renault would be
privatised.
'There is no certainty that there will be any privatisation before the next
(French) election,' said Mr Lars-Erik Forsgardh, head of Aktiespararna.
Analysts in Stockholm said that Volvo had not laid to rest the main concerns
over the merger. But they continued to doubted whether the large
institutional shareholders, who will decide the issue at the EGM, would see
any viable alternative.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Volvo.
    Renault.
    Branded Consumer Products.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>SEZ  Sweden, West Europe.
    FRZ  France, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
