<HEADLINE>
FT  27 OCT 93 / Thames Water hit by Pounds 25m charge
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PEGGY HOLLINGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THAMES Water yesterday surprised the market with lower than expected interim
profits, depressed by Pounds 25m of charges to cover two long-standing
contractual disputes.
The group, which had brought the announcement forward by a week, reported a
10 per cent decline in pre-tax profits to Pounds 112m for the six months to
September 30. Excluding the provisions, profits were 10 per cent up on sales
of Pounds 539m, a 7 per cent advance.
While the market was surprised by the charges, marking the shares down 13p
to 561p, analysts warned against taking them out of context in a company
with sales of Pounds 539m. 'The core business is excellent,' said one
analyst. 'Today's shenanigans have masked that.'
Next week's review of pricing in the water sector by Ofwat, the industry
regulator, would be more crucial for the market.
The charges, a small proportion of which applied to restructuring in the US,
are believed to cover two water treatment plants in Egypt. Thames acquired
the contracts when it purchased PWT in 1989 as part of its diversification
away from regulated utilities.
Mr Mike Hoffman, chief executive, admitted that PWT's contract management
had been deficient. About six employees had since left the company.
Mr Hoffman was unapologetic about Thames's diversification strategy, on
which it had spent some Pounds 120m. 'If we had sat back and stayed with
utilities we would be heroes,' he said, 'but there would be no growth. This
is for the longer term.'
During the half-year, Thames cut Pounds 2m in staff costs helping utilities
show an 18 per cent increase in operating profits to Pounds 159m, on sales 9
per cent higher at Pounds 432m.
However, the non-regulated activities were less buoyant. Contracting and
international businesses incurred pre-tax losses of Pounds 29m, after the
Pounds 25m charge, partly due to tough trading in Germany and the US.
Products and services slid to a Pounds 1.8m loss from a Pounds 400,000
profit, while environmental services lost Pounds 300,000. Property and
insurance profits rose from Pounds 1.2m to Pounds 1.8m.
Earnings per share fell 11 per cent to 26.8p. The dividend was increased 7
per cent to 7.4p.
