<HEADLINE>
FT  27 OCT 93 / Tarmac consortium aims to build second Forth bridge
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A CONSORTIUM of European construction companies has been formed by Tarmac
Construction to tender for the building of the second Forth road bridge. It
is the fourth consortium known to have registered an interest in the
project, which could cost Pounds 275m.
The government is expected to announce early next year whether it wants to
proceed with the new bridge. By next month it will have received feasibility
studies on the project, which would be privately funded and operated, and
earn revenue from tolls on the new and the existing bridges.
The Scottish Office will draw up a shortlist of three consortia to tender
for the project after the deadline for expressions of interest closes next
Tuesday. The project will involve building Pounds 100m worth of new roads.
Scottish Office ministers have already said they believe a new bridge will
be needed early next century because of the volume of peak-time traffic on
the existing bridge, which opened in 1964. Labour MPs have accused ministers
of having already decided to build a new bridge, while environmental groups
argue that it is not needed.
The consortium led by Tarmac includes the construction companies Bilfinger
and Berger of Germany, Bouygues of France, and HBM (Civil Engineering) of
The Netherlands, as well as Transroute, a French toll-road operator. It is
advised by Morgan Grenfell with lending to be led by NatWest Markets and
Banque National de Paris. The grouping is called E15, after the European
number of the road that crosses the Forth.
Other consortia to have declared their bids for the contract are: Forthspan,
led by Trafalgar House and Balfour Beatty, advised by Kleinwort Benson;
Forth Link, consisting of Taylor Woodrow, Sir Robert McAlpine, John Mowlem
and Morrison Construction, together with Dragados of Spain and Monberg and
Thorsen of Denmark, advised by Barclays de Zoete Wedd and John Laing,
GTM-Entrepose of France and Miller Group of Edinburgh, advised by Bank of
America.
The Scottish Office says that if the project proceeds the winning consortium
should be announced late next year or early in 1995. The project would then
have parliamentary procedures to go through, and possibly a public inquiry.
Construction could begin in 1996 or 1997 and could take four to six years.
Tarmac and Bouygues are partners in the Channel tunnel project, while
Bouygues is a leading partner in the Pont de Normandie in northern France,
which will be the world's longest cable-stay bridge.
