<HEADLINE>
FT  27 OCT 93 / Detection is 'best way' to hit crime
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT'S view that prison acts as a deterrent was further undermined
yesterday after Lord Taylor of Gosforth, the Lord Chief Justice, said the
rate of detection was far more important in combating crime.
His comment in a Lords debate on the report of the Royal Commission on
Criminal Justice comes after criticism by Lord Justice Woolf, a law lord, of
government proposals to crack down on crime.
Lord Woolf recently dismissed the policy of imprisoning greater numbers of
people as having a 'miserable record of failure'.
Mr John Major has given his public backing to his home secretary Mr Michael
Howard, who said prison works as a deterrent against crime.
Lord Taylor told peers: 'I am strongly of the view that the most important
deterrent to criminals is the likelihood of detection rather than the nature
or length of sentences. 'Will I get caught' is uppermost in the villain's
mind, not 'will I get three years or five'.
'Public interest at present is that the level of detection is low and, even
when detected, many offenders are not prosecuted. I hope that in its avowed
aim to give law and order high priority, the government will lay emphasis on
detecting and preventing crime and that all the resources necessary to that
emphasis will be made available.'
Lord Taylor's comments are an indication of the extent to which the legal
profession is at odds with the government's view of prison.
He yesterday repeated his opposition to removal of the right to elect for
jury trial in certain cases.
Referring to the planned review authority to deal with alleged miscarriages
of justice, he said it was important 'we should not proceed too fast'. It
was vital that it be properly set up.
</TEXT>
