<HEADLINE>
FT  27 OCT 93 / BR may win right to bid: Compromise considered to halt Tory
rebellion on railway sell-off
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT is considering a compromise over its railway privatisation
proposals which would allow British Rail to bid for some franchises under
certain conditions.
The potential compromise is designed to win over Conservative rail rebels
who support a Lords amendment giving BR the right to become a franchisee.
Ministers believe the Lords amendment would negate the effect of its
proposals because BR would have an in-built advantage in bidding against the
private sector.
Under the terms of the possible compromise discussed with some backbench
Conservative MPs, regarded as potential rebels, BR would have the right to
bid for some franchises - but less than half of the total.
The successful BR franchisees would have to operate as single units,
publishing separate and transparent accounts.
That condition would be designed to prevent BR submitting artificially low
bids for routes by cross-subsidising them with revenues from other services.
Lord Caithness, the government's transport spokesman in the Lords, recently
argued that allowing BR to bid for the franchises would 'undermine the whole
franchising process'.
BR's inside knowledge of the financial performance and potential of its
passenger services would give it an unfair advantage over the private sector
in pitching its bid, he said.
Supporters of railway privatisation fear that, irrespective of proposals to
stop cross-subsidising, BR would still win all the franchises if it were
allowed to take part. Putting a ceiling on the total number of franchises BR
could bid for would guarantee an element of competition from the private
sector.
At a meeting of the Conservative backbench committee on transport Mr John
MacGregor, transport secretary, yesterday declined to say whether he would
consider a compromise.
The Railways Bill is due to go back to the Commons from the Lords for its
third and final reading on Monday. If the cabinet decides to put forward new
proposals, they would take the form of a clause seeking to amend the Lords
amendment.
Mr MacGregor has been meeting Conservative MPs during the past few days and
privately brought up the possibility of a compromise.
One MP close to the minister said: 'The government will press ahead with its
rail privatisation proposals. But politics is the art of compromise and
ministers are confident they have a formula which will receive the support
of all Conservative backbenchers.'
The transport secretary has already climbed down twice over aspects of his
rail privatisation proposals. He agreed to commit the new rail regime to
maintaining concessionary railcards, and to write pensions guarantees into
the bill.
However, the concession over the industry's pension fund gained a frosty
response from the fund's trustees.
Mr Derek Fowler, trustee chairman, said in a letter to Mr MacGregor that he
is still concerned by the government's plans, which seek to water down its
obligations on Treasury contributions to the fund.
</TEXT>
