FT  27 OCT 93 / Thames signs Pounds 90m deal with ITV
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THAMES TELEVISION, the independent television production company that lost
its ITV franchise, announced yesterday that it had signed a deal to make
programmes worth more than Pounds 90m for the ITV Network Centre, the ITV
programme commissioning organisation.
The deal, which is spread over the next three years, is for The Bill, Des
O'Connor Tonight, Wish You Were Here and a range of other documentary, light
entertainment, comedy and children's programmes. Thames said the agreement
was the largest ever made in the UK with an independent producer and
confirmed the company's position as the leading independent studio.
Thames, which in April was bought by Pearson, owner of the Financial Times,
signed a deal in the summer with the BBC worth more than Pounds 20m over
three years. At the centre of that deal was This Is Your Life - originally a
BBC programme that later moved to ITV and will move back to the BBC next
autumn.
Under the deal with the ITV Network Centre, Thames will continue to produce
three weekly episodes of The Bill until the end of 1996. It has also been
asked to produce two more series of Des O'Connor Tonight for transmission in
1994 and 1995. The holiday programme Wish You Were Here is also being
prepared for transmission later this year, and will also be renewed for 1994
and 1995.
Mr Marcus Plantin, ITV Network director, said Thames' top programmes were
big audience winners. 'I'm delighted they are now guaranteed to remain on
ITV,' he said.
