<HEADLINE>
FT  27 OCT 93 / Campaigners opposed to rail privatisation descend on
Westminster
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
MORE THAN 1,000 campaigners opposed to rail privatisation descended on
Westminster yesterday to lobby MPs, while union leaders described the
sell-off plans as 'utterly destructive and sheer lunacy'.
Labour and Liberal Democrat MPs urged Tory MPs to join them in trying to
wreck the government's rail privatisation legislation currently going
through parliament.
The Save Our Railways group, which organised the action, produced a survey
of rail commuters showing that one in five could switch to cars if fares
increased under privatisation.
Mr Jimmy Knapp, general secretary of the largest rail union, the RMT, said:
'There is a deep and growing anger about the sheer lunacy of the
government's proposals.'
Other unions backed calls for Tory MPs to rebel and force through an
amendment to the railways bill which would allow BR to bid for franchises in
a privatised network.
Labour warned Tory MPs with small majorities: 'Save our railways or lose
your seats.'
Shadow employment secretary Mr John Prescott - Labour's former transport
spokesman - forecast two weeks of acrimonious debate in the Lords and
Commons.
'The bill is in a total mess, the Lords have torpedoed it below the water
line, and we will try to make it totally unworkable,' he said.
