<HEADLINE>
FT  27 OCT 93 / Motorcycle crowds hide declining industry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ABOUT 140,000 visitors are expected at the six-day Motor Cycle Show which
opened at Birmingham's National Exhibition Centre yesterday. That is about
three times the number of motorcycles the industry expects to sell in the
whole year.
While new car sales continue to recover, executives in the powered
two-wheeler market believe that at best their sector is bottoming out after
more than a decade of decline.
In 1980, Britons bought 315,000 motorcycles, scooters and mopeds. By last
year sales were down to 52,000 and Mr Graham Sanderson, spokesman for the
British Motorcycling Federation and an executive of market leader Honda,
yesterday said that sales were likely to fall further, to about 45,000 units
this year.
Mr Sanderson said the market would be doing well if this level was sustained
next year.
One consolation for importers, which control most of the market, and for the
resurgent Triumph Motorcycles, now the UK's only producer of any
significance, is that the value of machines sold has risen sharply.
Industry estimates find that more than two-thirds of all machines sold are
of 250cc and above, with many buyers being prepared to pay upwards of Pounds
6,000.
NEC show spokesman Mr Dennis Bates said that the majority of sales were made
to affluent over-35-year-olds who use motorcycles for leisure rather than
for essential transport. However, there is growing concern that young
people, on whom the market once relied, are no longer entering the sector
via mopeds and low-powered machines.
Honda, the world's biggest motorcycle maker which has about 30 per cent of
the UK market, has just returned to profitability in the UK after years of
losses obscured by its expanding cars business.
Midlands property entrepreneur Mr John Bloor remains confident about the
future of Triumph, the Leicestershire-based company he controls, which has
been making motorcycles with the Triumph badge for three years. Triumph has
already captured 13 per cent of the UK market for machines over 750cc.
</TEXT>
