<HEADLINE>
FT  27 OCT 93 / Smaller businesses 'maintain upturn'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE ECONOMIC recovery among smaller businesses remains robust, says a survey
published today.
The survey by the Association of British Factors and Discounters, whose
members provide cash for companies against unpaid invoices, found that
export sales grew by a third in the latest quarter in spite of mounting
concern about the effects of recession in continental markets.
'The recovery of Britain's smaller businesses is still intact,' said Mr Ben
Allen, association chairman.
Sales by clients of the association's members - 9,500 mainly small and
medium-sized companies - rose 22 per cent in the third quarter of the year
compared with the corresponding period last year. Although the annual rate
was slightly down on the 25 per cent achieved in the previous quarter, it is
the second-best figure recorded by the association in the past six years.
Mr Allen added: 'In contrast to other economic indicators in recent weeks,
our figures suggest that smaller firms paused for breath but did not drop
out of the race over the late summer.'
</TEXT>
