<HEADLINE>
FT  27 OCT 93 / Watchdog misinformed by MoD: Arms-for-Iraq inquiry told of
'ambiguous' status of ministry official
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE MINISTRY of Defence misinformed a Whitehall watchdog about links between
one of its officials and the proposed Pounds 1bn sale of Hawk trainer jets
to Iraq, the Scott arms-for-Iraq inquiry heard yesterday.
The official, Mr David Hastie, was appointed by the MoD in April 1988 as
'business development adviser' on secondment from British Aerospace where he
was a marketing executive.
Documents made available to the inquiry show that Mr Hastie was recruited
primarily because of his links to the Hawk sale, which was actively pursued
by BAe and MoD officials until the summer of 1989. The sale was stopped on
the insistence of Baroness Thatcher, the then prime minister.
In a letter written by the ministry to the Civil Service Commission in April
1989, asking to extend his contract, Mr Hastie was described as being
involved in the development of the European Fighter Aircraft and in helping
small businesses. No mention was made of the Hawk contract.
The commission supervises Whitehall recruitment, particularly non-advertised
appointments from the private sector.
Mr Ian McDonald, a senior MoD official, told the Scott inquiry yesterday
that Mr Hastie's appointment was judged by the ministry to be 'for the good
of HMG as well as for the company'.
Mr McDonald was questioned about previously secret government papers that
show Mr Hastie's appointment became the subject of controversy within
Whitehall.
Foreign Office officials vetoed a visit by Mr Hastie to the Baghdad
International Military Fair in April 1989 as an MoD official attached to the
ministry's defence export sales organisation.
They judged that Mr Hastie's status as an MoD official was 'ambiguous' and
risked being misinterpreted at a time when the government was bound by
guidelines restricting defence sales to Baghdad.
Subsequently Mr Hastie was allowed to be present at the fair without
official status but as a member of the BAe team.
Lord Justice Scott said that the documents made available to the inquiry
suggested a situation of 'conflicting duties'.
Subsequent answers to parliamentary questions about Mr Hastie, which were
prepared by Mr McDonald, were neither informative nor complete but amounted
to a 'fobbing off', the judge said.
The hearing continues tomorrow.
</TEXT>
