<HEADLINE>
FT  27 OCT 93 / Gloom forecast for finance sector
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A SHRINKING financial services industry in the south-east is leading to
fewer jobs and changing working patterns for employees, says a report
published yesterday.
The study by Hull and Bristol universities warns that the industry could be
facing a long-term decline after the shake-out in jobs and companies during
the past two years.
The report, published by the South East Economic Development Strategy, calls
for local authorities to take more interest in the provision of financial
services and for training and enterprise councils to develop training
programmes geared to the needs of local financial services employers.
Financial services was the key growth sector during the 1980s, says the
report. While overall employment in the UK remained constant in the 1970s
and 1980s, financial services doubled to nearly 2m people in the same
period.
Between 1990 and 1992 financial services employment fell by 11 per cent in
the south-east as companies retrenched and changed employment practices
under increased competitive pressures. 'At best, these changes will serve to
restrict the growth of financial services employment. At worst, employment
in the industry will experience a long-term decline,' says the report.
The report says the introduction of more part-time working as companies
reorganised has led to fewer opportunities for promotion among part-timers.
A Reversal of Fortune: Financial Services and the South East of England.
SEEDS, Latton Bush Centre, Southern Way, Harlow, Essex CM18 7BL. Pounds 75
(Pounds 25 for voluntary groups).
</TEXT>
