FT  27 OCT 93 / Lenders warn on mortgage relief
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MORTGAGE interest tax relief should be increased for first-time buyers and
remain unchanged for other home owners if the housing market's fragile
recovery is not to be jeopardised, the Council of Mortgage Lenders told the
government yesterday.
In its pre-Budget advice to Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, the council,
which represents building societies and centralised lenders such as banks,
warned that the housing market was on a knife-edge.
Mr Adrian Coles, the council's director-general, said: 'There is really very
little sign of the market recovering, despite a year of low interest rates
since sterling left the European exchange rate mechanism.'
The council also called for an interest rate cut and a successor to the
Business Expansion Scheme to bring repossessed houses back into use.
Mortgage interest available through income support to people who have lost
their jobs should not see further restrictions, it said.
Under its proposals, new buyers would be eligible for tax relief on loans up
to Pounds 60,000 in the first year, with that figure falling during the
first five years of the loan to the present limit of Pounds 30,000.
Any expansion of mortgage tax relief would be a severe change of direction
for the government, given the government's moves in recent Budgets to
restrict its scope.
</TEXT>
