<HEADLINE>
FT  27 OCT 93 / Three 'household name' insurers may face Lautro charges
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LAUTRO, the self-regulatory body for the life insurance industry, is
considering charges of widespread mis-selling against at least three of
Britain's largest and best known life insurance companies.
Lautro has not named the three companies, which are all publicly quoted. In
at least one of the cases, thousands of investors may be eligible for
compensation.
Charges against the companies centre around their failure to control
hard-sell sales tactics used by tied agents - those who sell a company's
products exclusively, but are not directly employed by the company.
The companies are accused of failure to monitor the sales agents to ensure
that they were giving best advice to investors. They are also accused of
failing to exercise due care in the recruitment and training of sales
agents.
While several 'household name' insurance companies have been the subject of
Lautro disciplinary actions, most actions have involved smaller, less
well-known insurers.
Lautro, which yesterday released its report on its enforcement activities
for the 12 months to June 30, said that in the latest year it had seen signs
of improving compliance with its rules on selling. But it noted 'that a
small number of the largest and most serious cases to occupy the Monitoring
Committee recently involved 'household name' life offices.'
Nevertheless, there were signs of improvement in the industry in the extent
to which it complied with Lautro rules on selling insurance. 'Members
performance appears better overall, though there is clearly still further
room for improvement,' the report said.
For instance, only 13 per cent to 16 per cent of life offices inspected
showed serious compliance shortcomings - down from 35 per cent during the
first round of inspection visits. Since Lautro began levying fines in 1992
for breaches of its rules, it has collected nearly Pounds 1m from companies.
Complaints from the public continued to grow, rising 35 per cent in the
period to 2,774. But Lautro noted that the rate of growth was lower than the
50 per cent recorded the year before.
Lautro's Monitoring Committee concluded in its report 'that the overall
improvement in standards needs to proceed further before Lautro can begin to
feel any real satisfaction at the success of its efforts'.
</TEXT>
<XX>
