<HEADLINE>
FT  27 OCT 93 / Pounds 1.5m bribes for MoD man alleged
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
A SENIOR Ministry of Defence official took backhanders totalling Pounds 1.5m
in exchange for contracts placed with three foreign ammunition suppliers, a
court heard yesterday.
For nearly five years Mr Gordon Foxley, the MoD's ammunitions procurement
director, arranged for sums to be channelled into Swiss bank accounts,
Snaresbrook Crown Court in London was told.
Mr Victor Temple QC, prosecuting, told the jury the money came from three
companies, Fratelli Bortelli, of Milan, Italy; Gubruder Junghans, based in
Schramberg, Germany; and AS Raufoss, with offices in Gjovik, Norway.
He alleged that Mr Foxley, now 69, entered into 'corrupt arrangements' with
each one. 'It was agreed that he would receive secret commissions from these
companies based on the value of orders he placed or caused to be placed with
the companies.'
Mr Foxley, now retired, of Henley-on-Thames, Oxfordshire, denies 12 charges
of corruption. Mr Temple claimed the payments - between December 1979 and
August 1984 - were based on 5 per cent of the contracts he arranged.
The case is expected to last two weeks.
</TEXT>
