FT  27 OCT 93 / Coup falters in Burundi
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LESLIE CRAWFORD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NAIROBI
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A military coup in Burundi appeared to be faltering yesterday after army
generals asked the prime minister to come out of hiding and form a new
civilian government, writes Leslie Crawford from Nairobi.
But there were doubts about the army's true intentions and surviving members
of the former government did not abandon their refuge in the French embassy
in Bujumbura.
Speaking from the embassy, Ms Sylvie Kinigi, the prime minister, called on
Burundi's military to return to their barracks. Her address, broadcast on
state radio, announced an end to the dusk-to-dawn curfew. She said the
borders and international airport would re-open soon.
Army generals on Monday asked her to form a new government, blaming the coup
and the assassination of President Melchior Ndadaye on a handful of mutinous
soldiers. But diplomats abroad said they believed that those now disowning
the coup had been its architects.
