<HEADLINE>
FT  27 OCT 93 / Mitsotakis quits as party chief
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KERIN HOPE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ATHENS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Constantine Mitsotakis, the Greek prime minister defeated by the
socialists in this month's general election, resigned yesterday as leader of
the conservative New Democracy party.
Mr Mitsotakis, 75, is the first of Greece's veteran political leaders
collectively dubbed the 'dinosaurs' to make way for a younger successor.
Four former cabinet ministers have declared themselves candidates for the
leadership. Mr Mitsotakis announced he would step down two weeks ago, when
Mr Andreas Papandreou's Panhellenic Socialist Movement won the election by a
larger margin than had been expected.
Frontrunner in the leadership contest is Mr Miltiades Evert, 54, who has
opposed the conservatives' privatisation policy. The new party leader will
be elected next week.
</TEXT>
