<HEADLINE>
FT  26 OCT 93 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow closes at record high in
late surge
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HAVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
AFTER A slow start, heavy demand for blue chip and cyclical issues sent the
leading US stock market index to an all-time high, writes Patrick Harverson
in New York.
At the close the Dow Jones Industrial Average was up 24.31 at 3,673.61,
comfortably eclipsing its previous record of 3,652.09 set in August.
Secondary indices fared less well. The more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's
500 ended 0.93 firmer at 464.20, the American SE composite down 1.67 at
475.58 and the Nasdaq composite off 2.93 at 769.75. Trading volume on the
NYSE was 260.3m shares.
Although investors started the week optimistic about the economy, concern
that stocks may be overpriced, with almost every major index at or near to
its record high, initially kept demand in check.
Also depressing sentiment were fresh worries about rising interest rates -
bond prices fell sharply for the third consecutive day yesterday, pushing
the yield on the benchmark 30-year bond up above 6 per cent.
There were, however, some positive factors at work in the market, such as
the latest developments in the bid battle for Paramount Communications, and
good news on monthly home sales. Eventually, investor sentiment recovered
and, amid steady buying of blue chip and cyclical stocks, the Dow posted a
strong gain in the final 90 minutes of trading.
The big corporate story of the day was Paramount, which climbed Dollars 1
1/2 to Dollars 79 in volume of 3.2m shares on news that Viacom had matched
the Dollars 4.8bn hostile takeover bid for the entertainment group made by
QVC Network, and had begun a tender offer for Paramount stock at a price of
Dollars 80 a share. The news left Viacom, traded on the American Stock
Exchange, down Dollars  3/8 at Dollars 59 and QVC, traded on the Nasdaq
market, Dollars 1 1/8 lower at Dollars 53 7/8 .
Among the cyclical stocks, Alcoa advanced Dollars 1 3/4 to Dollars 70 3/4 ,
Allied Signal firmed Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 72 7/8 and CSX added Dollars 1
at Dollars 78 3/8 . General Motors, however, retreated Dollars 1 1/2 to
Dollars 44 1/2 in volume of 5.57m shares after brokerage house PaineWebber
lowered its rating on the stock from 'buy' to 'neutral'.
Investors also seemed to be unsettled by the news that GM had agreed on a
three-year contract with the auto workers union which gives the company more
room to avoid paying laid-off workers but offers it little relief from
pension and medical costs.
Fresh rises in bond yields hurt bank and brokerage issues. Citicorp declined
Dollars  3/4 to Dollars 36 and Chase Manhattan gave up Dollars  3/4 at
Dollars 33 1/2 , while Merrill Lynch slipped Dollars  7/8 to Dollars 92 1/2
and Morgan Stanley Dollars 1 3/8 to Dollars 77 1/8 .
Canada
TORONTO finished virtually unchanged after a day of lacklustre trading ahead
of last night's federal election results.
The TSE 300 index inched up 1.4 to 4,155.3. The index had been down slightly
for most of the session, before staging a modest rally to move into positive
territory. Rises led falls by 381 to 368 after volume of 42.9m shares valued
at CDollars 468.3m.
Inco, off CDollars  1/2 at CDollars 26 5/8 , said its third-quarter earnings
rose to CDollars 91.2m from CDollars 10.6m a year earlier, but the latest
quarter included an after-tax gain of CDollars 127.9m from the sale of
Inco's stake in TVX Gold.
</TEXT>
